# Order Quality Assurance Framework

## Overview

Order quality assurance (QA) is a structured validation process designed to ensure that all purchase orders are accurate, compliant, and executable before they move into the fulfillment process.

A strong QA framework helps organizations reduce operational errors, prevent retailer chargebacks, and maintain high levels of customer satisfaction.

Wholesale operations teams typically own the QA process and act as the control point between order intake and operational execution.

---

# Purpose of Order QA

The primary goals of order quality assurance include:

• preventing incorrect orders from entering the fulfillment pipeline  
• ensuring pricing and product data accuracy  
• confirming inventory availability  
• validating compliance with partner routing and labeling requirements  
• identifying operational risks early  

By catching issues early, operations teams can resolve discrepancies before they impact logistics or financial operations.

---

# QA Validation Categories

Order QA should evaluate multiple categories of operational data.

## Product Validation

Verify that the products on the order are correct and properly configured.

Validation checks include:

• SKU existence in ERP system  
• correct product variants (size, color, configuration)  
• SKU mapping alignment between internal systems and partner catalogs  
• discontinued product detection

---

## Pricing Validation

Confirm that the pricing structure on the order is accurate and aligned with contractual agreements.

Checks include:

• wholesale pricing alignment  
• promotional pricing validation  
• discount accuracy  
• pricing tier verification

Incorrect pricing can lead to invoice disputes or financial losses.

---

## Quantity Validation

Ensure ordered quantities meet operational and packaging requirements.

Checks include:

• case pack alignment  
• minimum order quantities  
• pallet quantity rules if applicable  
• realistic demand levels

---

## Inventory Validation

Inventory availability should be verified before orders move forward.

Validation steps include:

• available-to-sell inventory confirmation  
• allocation conflicts with other orders  
• inventory location availability  
• backorder rules

---

## Compliance Validation

Many retail partners enforce strict compliance requirements that must be validated before shipment.

Common compliance checks include:

• retailer routing guides  
• labeling standards  
• carton and pallet configuration requirements  
• ASN requirements

Failure to meet compliance standards may result in retailer penalties.

---

# QA Process Workflow

A typical QA workflow includes the following steps:

1. Order intake review  
2. Product and SKU validation  
3. Pricing verification  
4. Quantity validation  
5. Inventory availability check  
6. Compliance requirement verification  
7. Approval for order processing

If discrepancies are detected, orders should be placed on hold until issues are resolved.

---

# Exception Handling

When QA issues occur, operations teams must document and resolve them efficiently.

Common QA exceptions include:

• invalid SKUs  
• pricing discrepancies  
• unavailable inventory  
• incorrect shipping details  
• compliance conflicts

Resolution may involve coordination with sales teams, account managers, or product teams.

---

# QA Escalation Protocol

If issues cannot be resolved quickly, escalation may be required.

Escalation scenarios include:

• large order discrepancies  
• repeated pricing errors  
• system integration failures  
• compliance risks with major retail partners

Escalations should follow defined internal communication channels to ensure rapid resolution.

---

# QA Metrics and Performance Tracking

Organizations should measure QA effectiveness using operational metrics.

Key metrics include:

• order accuracy rate  
• number of orders requiring correction  
• order hold rate due to QA issues  
• compliance violation frequency  
• retailer chargeback rate

Monitoring these metrics helps operations teams continuously improve the QA process.

---

# Continuous Improvement

QA frameworks should evolve as organizations scale and onboard new retail partners.

Improvements may include:

• automation of validation checks  
• system integration improvements  
• enhanced SKU data management  
• improved documentation and SOPs

A mature QA framework ensures operational reliability while supporting growth.
